If you want to lose weight, sure, eat less.  But if you want to get leaner and lose body fat, you need to eat enough daily, lift weights consistently and prioritize protein in your diet.
 Unfortunately, so many women have been taught to lose weight by eating less and focusing on the number on the scale.  If the scale isn’t consistently moving down, things must not be working.  Keep in mind, there is a difference between weight loss and fat loss.   With quick weight loss, you will lose fat AND metabolically healthy muscle- after the age of 30 we already lose between 3-5% of muscle mass each year through the aging process.  So, if you are chronically dieting, you will speed up this muscle loss leading to a weaker and frail older body. 
What you really want is fat loss, not weight loss - there is a difference.  The more muscle you have, you’ll increase your immune system response, cognitive function, and bone density.  You’ll burn more carbs and fat, reduce inflammation, have a better quality of life and look great too!  To get strong and lose body fat:  ✅ Eat enough food daily – No crash diets that are unsustainable   ✅ Eat more protein - Around .7-1g/lb   ✅ Strength train– A minimum of 3 days per week  Share if you agree!  If you are looking for help with this, check out the membership at NicoleWilkins.com. 𝗗𝗼 𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝗛𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗞𝗻𝗲𝗲 𝗣𝗮𝗶𝗻? PART 1

If you have been following me for a while, you know that I have struggled with knee pain on and off my entire adult life.  Two knee surgeries in my teens caught up to me a few years ago with tri-compartmentalized osteoarthritis.  I ended up getting Regenokine injections (an advanced form of PRP), which helped tremendously, however, it is a short term solution. 

In the meantime I need to continue taking good care of my knees to make sure I am able to stay active and slow down the advancement of the arthritis. 

Even if you don’t have knee pain, these tips are things that can help prevent that from happening too!  Here they are:

1- Get new/the right shoes
If you are running/training in shoes you have owned for 20+yrs, it is time to upgrade.  Head to a running store and get a gait analysis to determine the right shoe for you

2- Don’t Skip Your Warmup
You will most likely need to do this as you get older anyway, but it is good practice to properly prepare your body for work.  Get on the treadmill for 5min, add some dynamic stretching and then do 2-4 warm up sets before even beginning your first working set. It takes time, but you will thank me later.

3- Fix Your Form
Be sure you are executing each rep with proper form.  If you are unsure please ask a professional for help.

4- Mobility/Stretch
The tighter your muscle is (lack of mobility), the more likely your form will suffer and the risk of injury will increase. You may even want to consider taking yoga 🧘‍♀️

Are you struggling with knee pain? Here is part 2 👍

5-𝐒𝐭𝐫𝐞𝐧𝐠𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐧 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐥𝐞𝐠𝐬 𝐟𝐫𝐨𝐦 𝐚𝐥𝐥 𝐚𝐧𝐠𝐥𝐞𝐬.
Make sure you are working your quads AND hamstrings.  Your glutes AND your adductors.  Train your legs from all angles to keep the muscles around your knee strong.

6-𝐂𝐫𝐨𝐬𝐬-𝐓𝐫𝐚𝐢𝐧.
The more repetitive you are with a specific movement, the greater chance of injury if you are not careful.  For general health and fitness, mix it up.  Run one day, bike one day, elliptical one day, etc.

7-𝐋𝐨𝐬𝐞 𝐰𝐞𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐭.
This may or may not apply to you, but if you are overweight, it is causing more stress to the knees.  Consider tightening up your nutrition and or upping your physical activity.

Injuries are no fun, but sometimes small changes can make a big difference😉

6 Ways to Stop Sugar Addiction!

1. Eat more protein and healthy fats - this can help you feel more satisfied throughout the day and feel full longer

2. Cut back on added sugars in foods like sugary drinks and desserts and replace them with higher fibrous foods like fruit, veggies and whole grains.

3. Drink more water to stay hydrated.  Don’t mistake dehydration for hunger.

4. Go to bed 30 minutes earlier.  Lack of sleep can lead to an increase in sugar cravings

5. Find healthier alternatives if you want chocolate or desserts like fruit or dark chocolate

6. Seek support through a coach or other support group
 Remember, moderation is key but if your added sugar consumption is keeping you from reaching your goals, hopefully these tips will help!

If you have a foam roller but aren’t sure how to use it, this one is for you.

Foam rolling benefits include:
💪Improved flexibility
💪Improved range of motion/mobility when training
💪Increases blood flow and circulation
💪Reduces muscle soreness
💪Enhances delivery of nutrients aiding in recovery
💪Helps prevent injury
💪Eases pain and improves comfort

Here are 4 movements you can do for the lower body:
🔹Calves
🔹Quads
🔹Glutes (piriformis)
🔹Soleus

Start with the foam roller in the center of the muscle between the two joints.  Slowly move the roller 1-2 inches up or down and hold for about 10 seconds.  Repeat.

For added intensity on the calf stretch, cross your feet like I am to add more pressure, or bend the knee and straighten when rolling your quads like I show in the video.

I like to do this pre-workout to prep my muscles (and mind) for the work I am about to do, but the best part about foam rolling is you do not have to be warmed up to do it. 
It’s a hurt so good type of thing😅

So dust off your roller and give these a try- your body will thank you!

Building strength and muscle in your upper back during pregnancy can help reduce back pain and improve posture as the baby grows.

Here’s the workout:

🔹Tall-Kneeling Pulldowns 
🔹Lat Pulldowns (lighten the weight if you experience any doming in the midsection)
🔹Reverse Grip Barbell Row
🔹Seated Cable Rows
🔹One Arm Dumbbell Rows
🔹Hyperextension

Shoulder Workout🏋️‍♀️

I am almost half way through this pregnancy already!  Training 4x per week most weeks and trying to sustain as much strength as possible 💪  Energy has been much better this week too!

If your shoulder workout is typically programmed with rear delts at the end, try it in reverse with this training session to give them a bit more attention.  Rear delts help with posture (pulling the shoulders back) and are often much weaker than the other sides of the deltoid making it even more important to focus on them.

Perform straight sets resting 45seconds-1 minute 

4x10-15 of each increasing weight each set if applicable and form is ideal.

🔹Face Pulls
🔹Single Arm Cable Lateral Raise
🔹Upright Row/Front Raise Combo
🔹Seated Shoulder Press

Things I’ve learned from @misterbodhi 
.
1️⃣That structure to your day is important.  It gives him purpose.
2️⃣To stretch as much as possible.  He stretches every morning and each time he gets up #downwarddog and #upwarddog 😜
3️⃣To exercise daily (and outdoors as much as possible). Bodhi exercises twice a day at least! It keeps him sane 🙃 like his mommy
4️⃣To be more affectionate.  He loves to cuddle and be close, giving us kisses whenever possible.
5️⃣To always greet people with a smile.  Bodhi always drops what he’s doing to give us an undivided warm welcome every time we come home.
6️⃣To forgive and not hold grudges.  If I step on his paw, he yelps to let me know, but a few seconds later it’s as if it never happened.
7️⃣That persistence pays off. He keeps working and doesn’t give up when he really wants something.

22 Weeks!🥰

Just a few reasons why exercise is beneficial throughout pregnancy ❤️🤰

Although not often, I have heard things like: ‘Should you be doing that?’, ‘You’re going to hurt the baby!’, or ‘You should take it easy.’ 

It's important to remember that every pregnancy is unique, and pregnant individuals should be supported and respected in their choices regarding exercise and lifestyle. If you have concerns about a pregnant person's exercise routine, it's best to approach the topic with sensitivity and avoid making judgments or unsolicited comments.

Exercise during pregnancy is typically both safe and beneficial for many reasons as long as you have the go-ahead from your doctor to exercise and you do not have any contraindications.

Obstetrics & Gynecology 135(4):p 991-993, April 2020. | DOI: 10.1097/AOG.0000000000003773

EGGNOG PROTEIN SMOOTHIE 🥛🎄
 
INGREDIENTS
• 3/4 cup unsweetened coconut milk
• 1/4 cup pasteurized liquid egg substitute
• 1 small banana, frozen
• 1 scoop @npowernutrition Isolate Vanilla Cupcake protein powder
• 2 tbsp dry oats
• 3/4 tsp rum extract
• pinch ground nutmeg
• pinch ground cinnamon
• pinch salt
• 1/2 cup ice
*You will need: a high-powered blender

PREPARATION
• Put ice and banana into a high-powered blender. Pulse to break up.
• Add all remaining ingredients and blend on high until smooth and frothy, about one minute. 

Pour it into a couple of glasses to serve! If you’re feeling fancy, line the rims with a bit of protein powder and cinnamon. Enjoy! 😋

NOTE: use more or less ice depending upon how thick you like your shake.

NUTRITION INFO
(Per serving; recipe serves 2)
150 calories, 15g protein, 16g carbohydrates (2g fiber), 2.5g fat
